You&#39;re right.  You could catch the general exception with the fail
statement as you proscribed.  However, it is nice to know exactly
which exception is thrown, and in practice it&#39;s a little bit simpler
to set up a test method with all the exceptions that will be thrown
and then create new methods by copying this method and changing two
catch blocks. [Copying and pasting is the hallmark of great
programming.]


--- Vladimir Bossicard &lt;vladimir@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; &gt; The Junit.org site has an FAQ section
&gt; &gt; (http://junit.sourceforge.net/doc/faq/faq.htm) with the following
&gt; &gt; question: How do I implement a test case for a thrown exception?
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; The answer they give is not completely correct because it does
&gt; not
&gt; &gt; account for the possiblility that another exception could be
&gt; thrown.
&gt; 
&gt; I think they assume that your method only throws one exception.  If
&gt; your method throws more exceptions, you can use:
&gt; 
&gt; // Test IllegalArgumentException is thrown when partnerID is null.
&gt; public void test_00_isPartnerAssigned() {
&gt;    try {
&gt;       boolean assignedStatus =
&gt;          instancePartnerHierarchyWorker.isPartnerAssigned(null);
&gt;    } catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {
&gt;       return;
&gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt;       fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have been thrown.&quot;);
&gt;    }
&gt;    fail(&quot;IllegalArgumentException should have been thrown.&quot;);
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; -Vladimir
